\subsection{Causal Mechanisms}

In this section we empirically test causal mechanisms portrayed by our theory. We have posited that democratic high infrastructural power context is associated with higher investor confidence, which leads to inequality increases over time (\autoref{hypothesis:1}). At the same time, democratic rule under low capacity could inflict social instability, and lead to lower investor confidence harming the prospects for income concentration (\autoref{hypothesis:2}). We proxy investment climate quality with two different indicators used in previous literature: Fraser Institute's Economic Freedom Index \parencite{Gwartney:2017aa}, and Contract Intensive Money indicator \parencite{Clagueetal1996}. The advantage of these indicators compared to main alternatives relies in the fact that they are available for longer time-frames, similar to 1971-2016 period in our main analysis. Fraser Institute's indicator relies on expert evaluation of various aspects of business climate, such as degree of property rights protection, contract enforcement, legal freedom, trade openness and regulation of credit, labor and business. 




