Given that Fraser Index could be subject to biases stemming from expert judgment, we complement our analysis with a behavioral outcome relying on Contract Intensive Money (CIM) data. CIM is defined as the ratio of non-currency money to the total money supply, namely $\frac{M2-C}{M2}$, where M2 captures the money supply and C represents the currency outside banks \parencite{Clagueetal1996}. As \textcite{Clagueetal1996} note, it captures important aspects of business confidence and economic risks in the economy. An environment characterized by high investor confidence is associated with a higher proportion of contract-intensive money. When economic agents are less confident that their assets in banks will not be confiscated, potential investors will be less likely to be willing to conduct business, and the investment climate is perceived to be weaker \parencite{AriasHollyerandRosendoff2018}. A major advantage of the CIM relies in its coverage. Data are available since the beginning of our sample (i.e., 1960), for up to 120 developing countries




