We test our causal mechanism by asking if (a) democracy and high infrastructural power are positively associated with investor confidence, and (b) our business confidence indicators are significant predictors of inequality changes. We test these relationships using similar ECMs as in the main analysis. In Models 14 and 15, we estimate the interactive effect of Polity and Cumulative census on Fraser Institute's Economic Freedom Index, and CIM indicator, respectively. We do not document a significant effect of our interaction term on business confidence in these models \autoref{fig:interaction:model:14:plot}, but we find a positive and statistically significant association between both of our investor confidence variables and income inequality in Models 16 and 17. These results are mixed, but point to a direction that the interactive effect of democratic rule and infrastructural power posited in our main analysis might operate through investor confidence. We further probe the plausibility of out investor confidence mechanism through case study post-1994 South Africa. 


