\section{Democratization, State Capacity and Inequality in Post-Apartheid South Africa (1994-2010)}\label{south:africa:case}



In this section, we develop a case study of Post-Apartheid South Africa, which allows to illustrate how democratization under well-functioning market economy---backed by high state infrastructural power---contributed to higher income inequality through fomenting investor confidence. Although post-1994 South African democracy has achieved moderate success in both economic growth and human development, it has produced greater relative benefits to economic elites in top of the income pyramid.  

Before the fall of the Apartheid regime in 1994, South Africa was one of the most politically and socially unequal societies in the world. Formal institutions put in place by the apartheid state were based on segregationist laws that separated white and native inhabitants. Without a doubt, it was a system designed to promote the interests of the white minority during most of the 20th Century. The institutionalization of white dominance gave rise to very unequal land and income distribution. The Native Land Act in 1913 allocated 93\% of the agricultural land to the white population, while black South-Africans (around 59\% of the population) were forced to settle on the remaining  7\% of the land. 1920s, the Color Bar blocked black residents  from practically all skilled and professional occupations \parencite{Feinstein2005}. After 1948, the apartheid state implemented a wide array of measures to enforce social and educational segregation between whites and black South Africans. As a result, it became illegal for blacks to own property, or a business, in white neighborhoods In addition, many types of contractual relations were explicitly banned for black South Africans \parencite[21]{AcemogluandRobinson2015}.

Alongside of institutionalized economic discrimination, the South African state developed a remarkable ability to redistribute income through taxes and transfers from rich whites to poor whites. By 1980s the South African state was collecting more than 15\% of the  GDP per capita as income taxation, a burden that fell largely to the Afrikaner and English industrial, financial and landed elite. The development of the capacity to  collect income taxes, requiring considerable monitoring and assessment capabilities reflects the development of strong state institutions,\footnote{\textcite{Lieberman2003} argues that is redistributive state was made possible by extraordinarily strong cross-class unity between white upper classes and poor whites, which made the upper classes accept very high rate of taxation.} structured to produce ``quasi-voluntary compliance'' among  economic elites. 


The existing high income inequality resulting from racially-based discrimination, combined with an unprecedented level of state extractive capacity---at least in the developing world context---created a strong expectation that universal suffrage would produce equalizing redistributive taxation and pro-poor social policy. However, these predictions stemming from median voter logic have remained unfulfilled in post-Apartheid Africa. Paradoxically, the Gini Index of market income inequality, increased in a steady pattern from 65 to 69 between 1994 and 2010, while after tax and transfer inequality increased from 56 to 58. The state presence, in the form of taxes and transfers, has not been able to undo the dramatic increase in market income inequality after the introduction of democracy in 1994.\footnote{For instance, welfare policies such as social assistance grants (child support, disability grant, old age pensions) affect inequality only marginally, while contributing importantly to poverty reduction \parencite{Liebbrandt2010}.}

