A considerable part of inequality increases in South Africa could be explained by the greater  freedom movement of labor force between productive occupations in the Post apartheid era. With dismantlement of apartheid restrictions on labor movement in the end 1980s and early 1990s, and greater freedom of non-white workers to move to more productive occupations, inequality increased considerably within all racial groups, but especially so in the African population group \parencite{Liebbrandt2010,Pellicer2011}. However, alongside of these changes in the labor market, both the top 5\% and especially top 1\% have considerably increased their share in national income in the post-1994 period. The top 1\% income share rose from 11\% in 1990 to 18\% in 2010 \parencite{AlvaredoandAtkinson}. This could be partially explained by the fact that the decline of exclusionary labor market institutions not only contributed to greater dynamisms in the labor market, but also led to a decline of the labor costs for the manufacturing sector. During apartheid, exclusionary labor market institutions increased labor costs in the manufacturing sector, as they deprived industrialists from access to African labor force, which drove up the wages of white labor. Apartheid's institutional arrangements had clearly limited both the income share accruing to capital, and industrial development of apartheid-era South Africa. \footnote{Although manufacturing and financial elites accepted a very high tax burden during the Apartheid (mostly due to racial unity reasons), and there was no threat of expropriation by regime elites, their stance towards exclusionary institutions was always mixed at best \parencite[543]{Lieberman2003}. According to Acemoglu and Robinson (2015), the apartheid ``should be viewed as a coalition between white workers, farmers and mine-owners at the expense of blacks, but also white industrialists who had to pay very high wages for white workers'' (see also \textcite{Lundahl1982}).} The end of the apartheid allowed manufacturing elites to gain access to cheaper labor, which considerably expanded their profits \parencite[22]{AcemogluandRobinson2015}.


At the same time, the income concentration to the very top segment---mostly still composed of white business elites, but also by surging black business community favored by ruling African National Congress (ANC) affirmative action policies---cannot be solely explained by newly-found labor market freedom. It has been widely noted that the economic elites in financial and manufacturing sectors benefited from the end of the apartheid and the democratic transition in South Africa. We argue that these ``capital-boosting'' developments could be explained by the combination of democracy and high infrastructural power posited in our theoretical framework, which explain the relatively high business confidence and concentration of income to the top 1\% under democratization after 1994.  This is especially puzzling in the standpoint of median voter and power resource theories, which would predict redistribution via higher income tax rates, especially in a contexts where these policies are easily implemented.


First, South African democratic checks and balances crucially fomented investment security under uncertain conditions of high social conflict during transition period. Business confidence was fundamentally boosted by the veto actors in Parliamentary and Judiciary, which African National Congress (ANC) was facing after its election victory in 1994. In addition, realizing its structural dependency from English and Afrikaner capital under democratic politics, the ANC gave away its promises of radical land reform, nationalization of key conglomerates, and redistribution through pro-poor spending policies \parencite[543]{Habib1998}. The movement leaders quickly got rid of the most redistributive propositions the ANC had under the apartheid, while committing to  macroeconomic stability. Business communities also successfully exercised their  structural power, pressuring for lower capital tax rates and relaxed labor regulations \parencite{OECD2008} During Thabo Mbeki's presidency (1999-2008), regular meetings with business leaders within forums, such as the Big Business Working Group, were set up, demonstrating the government's efforts to satisfy business demands \parencite[398]{Davies2012}.



Democratization also facilitated the integration of South Africa into the world economy, which came to fundamentally benefit the economic elites. Already in 1990, Nelson Mandela had assured to international investors that no nationalization policy would follow after the end of the apartheid \textcite[543]{Habib1998}---a promise made credible by domestic institutional checks and balances limiting ANC rule. This could be interpreted as a clear sign of the ANC's ``structural dependency'' on domestic and international investment under democratic politics. Industrial and financial elites also benefited  from the end of international sanctions targeted against previous repressive regime. Indeed, South Africa experienced a considerable growth in its FDI stock between 1994 and 2008 \parencite{OECD2008} 

Second, pre-existing high quality institutions provided a fundamental basis for the smooth post-apartheid transition to market economy. South African experts generally recognize that the country has exceptionally strong legal and bureaucratic institutions in the African context \parencite{Mangcu2012}. During the apartheid era, the development of extractive capacity had gone hand in hand with the creation of relatively well-functioning bureaucracies, courts and financial system able to support a functioning national market economy.\footnote{South Africa has a sophisticated financial structure with the JSE Securities Exchange, a large and active stock exchange that ranked 18th in the world in terms of total market capitalization as of March 2009.} Although both corruption and crime have harmed the post-1994 business environment, South Africa inherited high-quality bureaucratic institutions able to implement decisions throughout their territory, and a robust and independent legal framework. 


It is reasonable to conclude that functioning national and local level bureaucratic institutions fomenting rule of law and contract security have fundamentally complemented democracy's capital-promoting features in South Africa. The combination of state capacity and democracy has crucially contributed to business confidence in the post-1994 era. For instance, the Heritage Foundation's Economic Freedom Index increased from 60.7 to 67.1 between 1995 and 2003 \parencite{Heritage:Foundation:2018}. Unfortunately, these two forces may have well contributed to higher market inequality during the  1994-2010 period, while also fomenting political power of capital, which was able to exert its influence on policy-making to demand lower capital taxation.  


\section{Conclusion}\label{conclusion}

In this paper we have explored whether the effect of democratic rule on income inequality could be conditional on state capacity. Counterintuitively, we argue that democratic rule combined with high state infrastructural power produce higher levels of income inequality, through the positive effect on investor confidence, which favors income concentration to the top. In essence, democracy offers protection of private property rights from arbitrary government involvement, benefiting economic elites and the business sector, while infrastructural power provides the preconditions for the functioning of capitalist market economy through legal and administrative institutions, which enhances private contracting among economic agents. We also argue that democratic rule reduces inequality under low state capacity, due to its potential to foster confidence-harming socio-economic conflicts in these settings.Our empirical results are robust to various measures of state infrastructural power and democracy. 


We interpret our results of giving further evidence to relative futility of two broad political economy approaches---median voter and selectorate models---when understanding political dynamics around income inequality (see influential theoretical criticisms of median voter model by \textcite[]{Haggard2012}, \textcite[]{Ansell:2014ty} and \textcite{AlbertusandMenaldo2018}, and of selectorate theory by \textcite{AlbertusFennerandSlater2018}. We believe that our work aligns well with recent contributions that have started to explore conditional hypotheses in democracy-redistribution link, like \textcite{AlbertusandMenaldo2018}. Future work could concentrate on interactive nature of political independent variables determining redistributive outcomes.


We also believe our conclusion speaks directly to recent literature on increasing inequality in the developed world, reflecting the natural tendency of well-functioning capitalism to produce higher income concentration \parencite[]{Piketty:2014aa}. Institutionalist literature has implicitly assumed that ``inclusive institutions'' do not only promote development, but also more equal income distribution, at least in the long term \parencite{AcemogluJohnsonRobinson2001}. In this paper, we have provided evidence that this conclusion may not be warranted, and ``inclusive'' institutions---captured in the combination of democratic regime type and high-capacity state institutions---might well increase income inequality through higher business confidence favoring economic elites. This income concentration might be self-reinforcing. Recent scholarship has widely documented the increasing influence of capital-concentrating elites in policy-making in democratic nations with well functioning state institutions capable of redistributing income with taxation and transfers. Our case study of South Africa suggests that similar industrial and financial elites were able to exercise enough influence to avoid any large scale redistribution in one of the most unequal societies in the world.      


